Possible Causes: Hub plus cannot detect a phase voltage on the grid side.
Recommended Action: Check that L1 and L2 terminations on the grid side are made properly and that the MIDC board is installed correctly. Check that the white connector at the top of the MIDC board is connected and seated properly.

Possible Causes: Hub plus cannot detect a phase voltage on the load side.
Recommended Action: Check that L1 and L2 terminations on the load side are made properly and that the MIDC board is installed correctly. Check that the white connector at the top of the MIDC board is connected and seated properly.

Possible Causes: Hub plus cannot detect a phase presence.
Recommended Action: Make sure production and consumption CTs are connected to the PVS.

Possible Causes: Inverter was loaded over its continuous capacity of 7.5kW.
Recommended Action: Make sure the loads on the back-up side are sized appropriately for the inverter power capacity.

Error Description: Could not detect one or more batteries
Custom Error Description: Could not detect one or more batteries
Possible Causes: We detected an odd number of batteries. We expect the system to have an even number fo batteries
Recommended Action: Please check that both batteries are turned on and that the ethernet cable connecting the batteries is properly placed. If the problem persists, please contact SunPower

Possible Causes: Low ambient temperature (below -10C) or faulty temperature sensor in Hub+
Recommended Action:
Check that the Hub+ door is closed. Ensure that no water or ice are present in the enclosure.
If ambient temperature is consistently above -10C, you may need to replace the part due to a faulty temperature sensor. Please contact SunPower.

Possible Causes: The Hub+ may be located in a hot location or facing direct sun. This could also be caused by loads/generation above Hub+ rating.
Recommended Action: Check that the Hub+ is not in direct sunlight and change its  location if that is the case. Check that loads and generation are within the ratings of the Hub+.

Possible Causes: Water intrusion into Hub+
Recommended Action: Ensure that the Hub+ door is closed and check for water intrusion.

Recommended Action: If a remote disconnect, also known as remote power off switch is needed, ensure the Remote power off switch is properly connected to the MIDC board. If this switch is not needed, you can ignore this warning.

Error Description: PVS could not connect to MIDC board
Custom Error Description: PVS could not connect to MIDC board
Possible Causes:
The PVS cannot connect with the MIDC board. The MIDC board drives the transfer switch on the Hub+. It also connects to the MIO board, so if you’re seeing this error, it is likely that other errors are occurring as well. You should focus on fixing this error first before you proceed to fix the others.

This problem may be due to one of the following causes:
1. The MIDC board is not powered
2. The MIDC board is not connected to the MIO board.
3. PVS MIDC CAN connector is bad
4. The MIDC board is damaged
5. The AUX cable between inverter and MIDC board is not properly connected and/or terminated.
Recommended Action:
Please try the following steps
1. Check that the line-side and load-side AC cables to the MIDC board.
2. Check that the gray ethernet cable and connectors between the MIDC (J14) and/or PV disconnect relay board and MIO (J1) board is connected and terminated properly.
3. Check that PVS MIDC CAN (J13) connector board cable is in place
4. Check that the gray cable between the Aux port on the inverter and the J16 port on the MIDC board is correctly connected and terminated.
5. Press the retry button in the app.

If the problem persists, this may be a sign that the MIDC board is damaged. Please contact SunPower.

Error Description: PVS could not connect to MIO board
Custom Error Description: PVS could not connect to MIO board
Possible Causes:
The PVS cannot connect with the MIO board. The MIO board is a hub for data connections to the batteries, inverter, and gateway, so if you’re seeing this error, it is likely you’re also seeing other errors such as missing batteries or inverters.

This problem may be due to one of the following causes:
1. Faulty data connection between the Hub+ and the MIO board.
2. MIO lost power.
3. Faulty data connection with another MIO board (applicable to Power Expansion packs only)
Recommended Action:
Please try the following steps:
1. Check that the MIO board is powered: one LED should be blinking and the other one should be solid.
2.  Check that the gray ethernet cable from the J1 port on the MIO board is connected to the J14 port on the MIDC and/or PV disconnect relay board. Check that the cable is terminated correctly.
3. Check that the 48V DC connection on the MIO board is connected to the DC terminals on the inverter and properly grounded and terminated.
4. Press the retry button on the app.

If the problem persists, this may be a sign that the MIO board is damaged. Please contact SunPower.

Error Description: PVS could not connect to ESS Gateway
Custom Error Description: PVS could not connect to ESS Gateway
Possible Causes:
The Schneider Gateway connects the inverter with PVS and batteries. If you’re seeing this error it is likely you’re also seeing other errors such as batteries  or inverter(s) missing.

This problem may be due to the following causes:
1. Gateway lost power.
2. The ethernet connector between the gateway and PVS is not connected or terminated correctly.
3. Gateway may need to be rebooted.
Recommended Action:
1. Check that the gateway has power: the LEDs should be blinking.
2. Check that the green cable and its orange, orange/white, green, blue and blue/white conductors in the metal ferules on the gateway side are properly connected to the J4 port on the MIO board.
3. Check the black ethernet cable is connected to the black ethernet port on the PVS. Check also that the cable is correctly terminated.
4. Check that the cable mentioned in 3 is connected to the port labeled as ‘ethernet’ on the Schneider gateway.
5. Reboot the gateway. In order to do so:
     a. Disconnect the yellow ethernet cable from its port on the left side of the gateway.
     b. Disconnect the black ethernet cable from its port on the left side of the gateway.
     c. Disconnect the green ethernet cable from the J4 port on the right side of the Multi I/O (MIO) board.
     d. Wait for about 30 seconds.
     e. Reconnect all the cables mentioned in sections 5a through 5c.
     f. Wait for the LEDs show gateway is in normal operation (see manual).
6. Press 'retry' on the commissioning app.

If the problem persists, this may be a sign that the Schneider Gateway is damaged. Please contact SunPower.

Error Description: PVS could not connect to inverter
Custom Error Description: PVS could not connect to inverter
Possible Causes:
The PVS cannot connect to the Schneider inverter.
1.  If you’re also seeing an error that indicates that the gateway is missing, this error may be due to the fact that the gateway is not properly connected. Please address the problem with the gateway first if you're seeing a gateway error.
2. The inverter may need to be rebooted.
3. A data connection between the inverter.MIO and PVS is not properly made.
Recommended Action:
Please try the following steps:
1. If you're also seeing a 'missing gateway' error, please try to fix that problem first following the instructions in the 'missing gateway' error message.
2. Reboot the inverter by pressing the 'on/off' button on the XWPro inverter for a few seconds until you see 'OFF' appear on the inverter display, then press the 'on/off' button again
3. Press the retry button on the app.
If the problem persists:
1. Check that the yellow XANBUS connector between the Schneider gateway and the inverter is correctly terminated and connected to the port labeled as XANBUS in he inverter (underneath the inverter, to the right of the SYNC port left of BTS port and AUX ports).
2. Check that the RPO cable in the inverter (port labeled as BTS) is connected to the J5 (red) termination in the MIO board.
3. Check that any of LEDs on inverter are On.
4. Check that the DC conductors have at least 48V between terminations.
5. Ensure that the DC terminations are done correctly
6. Ensure that the DC breakers are closed.
7. Ensure that the batteries are on. If not, press the ON button on the batteries.
8. Check that the gray AUX connector from the inverter is connected to the J16 termination on the MIDC board.
9. Press retry on the commissioning app.

If the problem persists, this may be a sign that the inverter is damaged. Please contact SunPower.

Error Description: PVS could not connect to batteries
Custom Error Description: PVS could not connect to batteries
Possible Causes:
The PVS cannot connect with the batteries. This could be due because there are other connections missing. If you’re also seeing a missing gateway error, missing MIDC or missing MIO board, this ’No BMS’ error is likely due to any of these errors and you should try to fix them before you attempt to fix this.

This problem may be due to the following causes:
1. Gateway is not connected. If this is the case, you’ll also be seeing a ‘No gateway’ error and you should attempt fixing the problem first.
2. CAN bus connection (green) between the MIO board (J4) and Schneider gateway is not properly made.
3. The CAN bus connection on the Gateway side is not properly made or terminated (white-orange, orange, white-green, white-blue, and blue conductors).
4. The CAN cable between J4 port on MIO and gateway is cut off.
5. Connection between the batteries (orange) and the MIO board is not properly made
6. Batteries are not powered on.
Recommended Action:
Please try the following steps
1. If you’re also seeing a ‘missing gateway’ error, please try to fix that problem first following the instructions in the error message.
3. Check that the CAN bus connection on the Gateway side is not properly made or terminated (white-orange, orange, white-green, white-blue, and blue conductors).
3. Check that the orange cable between the master battery and the MIO board is properly connected and terminated.
4. Check that the batteries are powered on (check status of LEDs around the power button on the side of the batteries).
5. Check that the DC breakers are on the closed position.
6. Press 'retry' on the pre-discovery screen in the commissionning app.
7. If the problem persists, attempt rebooting the batteries by pressing the 'off' button on the side of each battery and turn them back on.

If the problem still persists, this may be a sign that one or more batteries are damaged. Please contact SunPower.

Recommended Action: N/A

6. Press 'retry' on the pre-discovery screen in the commissionning app.
7. If the problem persists, attempt rebooting the batteries by pressing the 'off' button on the side of each battery and turn them back on.

If the problem still persists, this may be a sign that one or more batteries are damaged. Please contact SunPower.

Error Description: PVS could not connect to one or more inverters
Custom Error Description: PVS could not connect to one or more inverters
Possible Causes:
The PVS cannot connect to the Schneider inverter.
1.  If you’re also seeing an error that indicates that the gateway is missing, this error may be due to the fact that the gateway is not properly connected. Please address the problem with the gateway first if you're seeing a gateway error.
2. The inverter may need to be rebooted.
3. A data connection between the inverter.MIO and PVS is not properly made.
Recommended Action:
Please try the following steps:
1. If you’re also seeing a ‘missing gateway’ error, please try to fix that problem first following the instructions in the 'missing gateway' error message.
2. Reboot the inverter by pressing the 'on/off' button on the XWPro inverter for a few seconds until you see 'OFF' appear on the inverter display, then press the 'on/off' button again
3. Press the retry button on the app.
If the problem persists:
1. Check that the yellow XANBUS connector between the Schneider gateway and the inverter is correctly terminated and connected to the port labeled as XANBUS in he inverter (underneath the inverter, to the right of the SYNC port left of BTS port and AUX ports).
2. Check that the RPO cable in the inverter (port labeled as BTS) is connected to the J5 (red) termination in the MIO board.
3. Check that any of LEDs on inverter are On.
4. Check that the DC conductors have at least 48V between terminations.
5. Ensure that the DC terminations are done correctly
6. Ensure that the DC breakers are closed.
7. Ensure that the batteries are on. If not, press the ON button on the batteries.
8. Check that the gray AUX connector from the inverter is connected to the J16 termination on the MIDC board.
9. Press retry on the commissioning app.

If the problem persists, this may be a sign that the inverter is damaged. Please contact SunPower.

Error Description: PVS could not connect to MIO board
Custom Error Description: PVS could not connect to MIO board
Possible Causes:
The PVS cannot connect with the MIO board. The MIO board is a hub for data connections to the batteries, inverter, and gateway, so if you’re seeing this error, it is likely you’re also seeing other errors such as missing batteries or inverters.

This problem may be due to one of the following causes:
1. Faulty data connection between the Hub+ and the MIO board.
2. MIO lost power.
3. Faulty data connection with another MIO board (applicable to Power Expansion packs only)
Recommended Action:
Please try the following steps:
1. Check that the MIO board is powered: one LED should be blinking and the other one should be solid.
2.  Check that the gray ethernet cable from the J1 port on the MIO board is connected to the J14 port on the MIDC and/or the PV disconnect relay board. Check that the cable is terminated correctly.
3. Check that the 48V DC connection on the MIO board is connected to the DC terminals on the inverter and properly grounded and terminated.
4. Press the retry button on the app.

If the problem persists, this may be a sign that the MIO board is damaged. Please contact SunPower.

Recommended Action: N/A

Error Description: PVS could not connect to batteries
Custom Error Description: PVS could not connect to batteries
Possible Causes:
The PVS cannot connect with the batteries. This could be due because there are other connections missing. If you’re also seeing a missing gateway error, missing MIDC or missing MIO board, this ’No BMS’ error is likely due to any of these errors and you should try to fix them before you attempt to fix this.

This problem may be due to the following causes:
1. Gateway is not connected. If this is the case, you’ll also be seeing a ‘No gateway’ error and you should attempt fixing the problem first.
2. CAN bus connection (green) between the MIO board (J4) and Schneider gateway is not properly made.
3. The CAN bus connection on the Gateway side is not properly made or terminated (white-orange, orange, white-green, white-blue, and blue conductors).
4. The CAN cable between J4 port on MIO and gateway is cut off.
5. Connection between the batteries (orange) and the MIO board is not properly made
6. Batteries are not powered on.
Recommended Action:
Please try the following steps
1. If you’re also seeing a ‘missing gateway’ error, please try to fix that problem first following the instructions in the error message.
3. Check that the CAN bus connection on the Gateway side is not properly made or terminated (white-orange, orange, white-green, white-blue, and blue conductors).
3. Check that the orange cable between the master battery and the MIO board is properly connected and terminated.
4. Check that the batteries are powered on (check status of LEDs around the power button on the side of the batteries).
5. Check that the DC breakers are on the closed position.
6. Press 'retry' on the pre-discovery screen in the commissionning app.
7. If the problem persists, attempt rebooting the batteries by pressing the 'off' button on the side of each battery and turn them back on.

If the problem still persists, this may be a sign that one or more batteries are damaged. Please contact SunPower.

Error Description: PVS could not connect to ESS Gateway
Custom Error Description: PVS could not connect to ESS Gateway
Possible Causes:
The Schneider Gateway connects the inverter with PVS and batteries. If you’re seeing this error it is likely you’re also seeing other errors such as batteries  or inverter(s) missing.

This problem may be due to the following causes:
1. Gateway lost power.
2. The ethernet connector between the gateway and PVS is not connected or terminated correctly.
3. Gateway may need to be rebooted.
Recommended Action:
1. Check that the gateway has power: the LEDs should be blinking.
2. Check that the green cable and its orange, orange/white, green, blue and blue/white conductors in the metal ferules on the gateway side are properly connected to the J4 port on the MIO board.
3. Check the black ethernet cable is connected to the black ethernet port on the PVS. Check also that the cable is correctly terminated.
4. Check that the cable mentioned in 3 is connected to the port labeled as ‘ethernet’ on the Schneider gateway.
5. Reboot the gateway by  pulling the ethernet connectors from the left-side of the Gateway and plugging them back into the same ports they were in. It may take a few minutes for the gateway to reboot.
6. Press 'retry' on the commissioning app.

If the problem persists, this may be a sign that the Schneider Gateway is damaged. Please contact SunPower.

Error Description: PVS could not connect to MIDC board
Custom Error Description: PVS could not connect to MIDC board
Possible Causes:
The PVS cannot connect with the MIDC board. The MIDC board drives the transfer switch on the Hub+. It also connects to the MIO board, so if you’re seeing this error, it is likely that other errors are occurring as well. You should focus on fixing this error first before you proceed to fix the others.

This problem may be due to one of the following causes:
1. The MIDC board is not powered
2. The MIDC board is not connected to the MIO board.
3. PVS MIDC CAN connector is bad
4. The MIDC board is damaged
5. The AUX cable between inverter and MIDC board is not properly connected and/or terminated.
Recommended Action:
Please try the following steps
1. Check that the line-side and load-side AC cables to the MIDC board.
2. Check that the gray ethernet cable and connectors between the MIDC (J14) board and MIO (J1) board is connected and terminated properly.
3. Check that PVS MIDC CAN (J13) connector board cable is in place
4. Check that the gray cable between the Aux port on the inverter and the J16 port on the MIDC board is correctly connected and terminated.
5. Press the retry button in the app.

If the problem persists, this may be a sign that the MIDC board is damaged. Please contact SunPower.

Possible Causes:
This error may be due to one of the following causes:
- Internal temperature is over 105C
- AC input voltage may be too high while charging
- Operating too large of a load for too long
- Inverter cooling fan may have failed
- Inverter airflow intake may be blocked
- Charging setting is to high based on ambient temperature around inverter
Recommended Action:
Depending on the cause try one of the following:
- AC input voltage high: check for high input AC voltage.
- High loads: remove excessive loads.
- Failed inverter fan: hold a piece of paper to inverter vents to check the fan. If the fan has failed, have the inverter serviced.
- Inverter airflow intake may be blocked: increase clearance around the inverter or unclog the fan air intake.
- Charging setting too high: lower the max charge rate setting

Recommended Action: Check for loads above the inverter's capacity. Turn off some loads if necessary. To clear the fault: Turn off th eunit by holding the power button for 5 sec. Disconnect the Conext XW Pro Inverter from the battery bank for 20 seconds.

Possible Causes: Multi-unit configuration settings are incorrect.
Recommended Action: Ensure only one unit is configured as the master. Ensure each unit has a unique Device Number and that connections have been configured correctly. Ensure there is only one primary charger.

Possible Causes: Inverter firmware error.
Recommended Action: Service required.

Possible Causes: The transformer temperature is over 140C.
Recommended Action: The fault clears when the transformer temperature falls to 125C. Ensure adequate ventilation around the Conext XW Pro inverter. Reduce AC loads.

Possible Causes: Inverter could not synch with the grid.
Recommended Action: Check connections and cable on external AC sync port. In a signle-inverter system, nothing must be plugged into the AC sync port. Clear fault and try again. If these steps fail, the unit requires service.

Possible Causes:

- Check that the conductors are terminated correctly and in the right order on both ends of the cable.

Possible Causes:
The PVS cannot connect with the batteries. This could be due because there are other connections missing. If you’re also seeing a missing gateway error, missing MIDC or missing MIO board, this ’No BMS’ error is likely due to any of these errors and you should try to fix them before you attempt to fix this.

This problem may be due to the following causes:
1. Gateway is not connected. If this is the case, you’ll also be seeing a ‘No gateway’ error and you should attempt fixing the problem first.
2. CAN bus connection (green) between the MIO board (J4) and Schneider gateway is not properly made.
3. The CAN bus connection on the Gateway side is not properly made or terminated (white-orange, orange, white-green, white-blue, and blue conductors).
4. The CAN cable between J4 port on MIO and gateway is cut off.
5. Connection between the batteries (orange) and the MIO board is not properly made
6. Batteries are not powered on.
Recommended Action:
Please try the following steps
1. If you’re also seeing a ‘missing gateway’ error, please try to fix that problem first following the instructions in the error message.
3. Check that the CAN bus connection on the Gateway side is not properly made or terminated (white-orange, orange, white-green, white-blue, and blue conductors).
3. Check that the orange cable between the master battery and the MIO board is properly connected and terminated.
4. Check that the batteries are powered on (check status of LEDs around the power button on the side of the batteries).
5. Check that the DC breakers are on the closed position.
6. Press 'retry' on the pre-discovery screen in the commissionning app.
7. If the problem persists, attempt rebooting the batteries by pressing the 'off' button on the side of each battery and turn them back on.

If the problem still persists, this may be a sign that one or more batteries are damaged. Please contact SunPower.

Error Description: Inverter cannot communicate with the gateway.
Custom Error Description: Inverter cannot communicate with the gateway.
Possible Causes:
The Schneider Gateway connects the inverter with PVS and batteries. If you’re seeing this error it is likely you’re also seeing other errors such as batteries  or inverter(s) missing.

This problem may be due to the following causes:
1. Gateway lost power.
2. The ethernet connector between the gateway and PVS is not connected or terminated correctly.
3. Gateway may need to be rebooted.
Recommended Action:
1. Check that the gateway has power: the LEDs should be blinking.
2. Check that the green cable and its orange, orange/white, green, blue and blue/white conductors in the metal ferules on the gateway side are properly connected to the J4 port on the MIO board.
3. Check the black ethernet cable is connected to the black ethernet port on the PVS. Check also that the cable is correctly terminated.
4. Check that the cable mentioned in 3 is connected to the port labeled as ‘ethernet’ on the Schneider gateway.
5. Reboot the gateway by  pulling the ethernet connectors from the left-side of the Gateway and plugging them back into the same ports they were in. It may take a few minutes for the gateway to reboot.
6. Press 'retry' on the commissioning app.

If the problem persists, this may be a sign that the Schneider Gateway is damaged. Please contact SunPower.

Error Description: Inverter cannot communicate with the PVS
Custom Error Description: Inverter cannot communicate with the PVS
Possible Causes:
Schneider Connext XW Pro inverter cannot connect to PVS.
1.  If you’re also seeing an error that indicates that the gateway is missing, this error may be due to the fact that the gateway is not properly connected. Please address the problem with the gateway first if you're seeing a gateway error.
2. The inverter may need to be rebooted.
3. A data connection between the inverter.MIO and PVS is not properly made.
Recommended Action:
Please try the following steps:
1. If you’re also seeing a ‘missing gateway’ error, please try to fix that problem first following the instructions in the 'missing gateway' error message.
2. Reboot the inverter by pressing the 'on/off' button on the XWPro inverter for a few seconds until you see 'OFF' appear on the inverter display, then press the 'on/off' button again
3. Press the retry button on the app.
If the problem persists:
1. Check that the yellow XANBUS connector between the Schneider gateway and the inverter is correctly terminated and connected to the port labeled as XANBUS in he inverter (underneath the inverter, to the right of the SYNC port left of BTS port and AUX ports).
2. Check that the RPO cable in the inverter (port labeled as BTS) is connected to the J5 (red) termination in the MIO board.
3. Check that any of LEDs on inverter are On.
4. Check that the DC conductors have at least 48V between terminations.
5. Ensure that the DC terminations are done correctly
6. Ensure that the DC breakers are closed.
7. Ensure that the batteries are on. If not, press the ON button on the batteries.
8. Check that the gray AUX connector from the inverter is connected to the J16 termination on the MIDC board.
9. Press retry on the commissioning app.

If the problem persists, this may be a sign that the inverter is damaged. Please contact SunPower.

Possible Causes: Something went wrong while updating Conext XW Pro inverter.
Recommended Action: Ensure the app has downloaded the ESS firmware in full. Try updating firmware again. If the problem persists, please contact SunPower.

Error Description: PVS could not connect to ESS Gateway
Custom Error Description: PVS could not connect to ESS Gateway
Possible Causes:
The Schneider Gateway connects the inverter with PVS and batteries. If you’re seeing this error it is likely you’re also seeing other errors such as batteries  or inverter(s) missing.

This problem may be due to the following causes:
1. Gateway lost power.
2. The ethernet connector between the gateway and PVS is not connected or terminated correctly.
3. Gateway may need to be rebooted.
Recommended Action:
1. Check that the gateway has power: the LEDs should be blinking.
2. Check that the green cable and its orange, orange/white, green, blue and blue/white conductors in the metal ferules on the gateway side are properly connected to the J4 port on the MIO board.
3. Check the black ethernet cable is connected to the black ethernet port on the PVS. Check also that the cable is correctly terminated.
4. Check that the cable mentioned in 3 is connected to the port labeled as ‘ethernet’ on the Schneider gateway.
5. Reboot the gateway by  pulling the ethernet connectors from the left-side of the Gateway and plugging them back into the same ports they were in. It may take a few minutes for the gateway to reboot.
6. Press 'retry' on the commissioning app.

If the problem persists, this may be a sign that the Schneider Gateway is damaged. Please contact SunPower.

Possible Causes: Could not update gateway firmware.
Recommended Action:
1. Reboot the gateway by  pulling the ethernet connectors from the left-side of the Gateway and plugging them back into the same ports they were in. It may take a few minutes for the gateway to reboot.
2. Try updating the firmware again.
If the problem persists, please contact SunPower.

Possible Causes: Could not update settings in the inverter.
Recommended Action:
1. Reboot the gateway. In order to do so:
     a. Disconnect the yellow ethernet cable from its port on the left side of the gateway.
     b. Disconnect the black ethernet cable from its port on the left side of the gateway.
     c. Disconnect the green ethernet cable from the J4 port on the right side of the Multi I/O (MIO) board.
     d. Wait for about 30 seconds.
     e. Reconnect all the cables mentioned in sections 5a through 5c.
     f. Wait for the LEDs show gateway is in normal operation (see manual).
2. Try applying bulk settings again by tapping 'retry' or running the firmware update step again.
If the problem persists, please contact SunPower.
